our distinguished architects?<lb/>
Poietes. I am not a craniologist,<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="88"
                xml:id="pb-88"
                facs="#i88"/>
            <lb/>
always fly when their appetite is satis-<lb/>
=fied; a <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">wren</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">hen</add> in defending her chickens<lb/>
against a powerful dog, or the game<lb/>
cock in fighting for the female, or<lb/>
the timid hart at the time of the<lb/>
sexual intercourse show quite as<lb/>
much of this quality as the most<lb/>
ferocious royal tyger. Courage is<lb/>
the result of strong passions or strong<lb/>
motives, &amp; in man it usually re-<lb/>
=sults from the love of glory or the<lb/>
fear of shame &amp; it appears to me<lb/>
