153<lb/>
"See the birth of time! look at man in<lb/>
his newly created state full of youth &amp;<lb/>
vigour, <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">dost thou</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">Did you</add> see aught in this state to<lb/>
admire or to envy." As the last words fell on<lb/>
my ear I was again as before rapidly put<lb/>
in motion &amp; I seemed again resistless to be<lb/>
hurried upon a stream of air &amp; again in<lb/>
perfect darkness: In a moment <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">as before</del> an<lb/>
indistinct light again appeared before any<lb/>
